# Global `CLAUDE.md` — opinionated starter template

This is the file that lives at `~/.claude/CLAUDE.md` and is loaded into every Claude Code session. It tells Claude how *you* want to work.

**Use this as a starting point — not a finished file.** Many of these rules are opinions distilled from real failures, but your workflow, OS, and tooling will be different. Read each rule, keep the ones that match your reality, swap the rest. Anything marked **[OPINION]** is where your taste differs most from someone else's; anything marked **[UNIVERSAL]** is platform/safety behaviour you almost certainly want.

---

## How to use this template

1. Copy the markdown below into `~/.claude/CLAUDE.md` (Windows: `C:\Users\<you>\.claude\CLAUDE.md`).
2. Replace `[OPINION]` blocks with your own preferences.
3. Delete sections that don't apply (e.g., the SQL Server / Bitdefender rule is specific to that stack).
4. Restart Claude Code so the new instructions load.
5. Re-read it every few months — your workflow drifts, the file should drift with it.

---

## Template

```markdown
# Global instructions for Claude Code

## Things I handle myself — don't do them unsolicited

<!-- [OPINION] — keep, edit, or remove based on your workflow. -->

- **Git commits / pushes** — I do all git operations.
- **Starting servers** (e.g., `node src/server.js`) — I start them manually.
- **Installing software/packages** (npm, pip, choco, winget, etc.) — explain what + why, wait for explicit approval. A PreToolUse hook (e.g., `block-installs.py` from claude-code-essentials) enforces this. After approval, append ` # APPROVED` to the command (e.g., `pip install dbt-core # APPROVED`).

## Environment

<!-- [OPINION] — the shell choice is yours. The "read before edit" rule below is [UNIVERSAL]. -->

- Shell is **<your shell>** (e.g., bash, zsh, PowerShell). Use the matching command names.
- **[UNIVERSAL] Always read a file before editing it.** Claude Code's Edit tool fails otherwise. When editing several files in parallel, read them all first in one batch.
- **[OPINION]** After agents finish, clean up any `tmpclaude-*` and `nul` temp files left behind.

## Standard project folders

<!-- [OPINION] — this folder convention is one workable pattern, not the only one.
     Adopt, adapt, or replace with your own. Whatever you pick, write it down here
     so every session reuses the same vocabulary. -->

Create as needed:
- `_Research/` — research outputs. Screenshots → `_Research/Printscreens/`.
- `_Plan/` — implementation plans. Every plan must include testing, security, and success criteria. Mark completed plans `name - Completed.md`. Plans created by `/plan` (which live at `~/.claude/plans/*.md`) should be copied into `_Plan/` with a meaningful filename — the repo copy is canonical.
- `_Plan/Backlog.md` — work-item table: Backlog Item, Epic, Plan File (with line ranges, e.g., `_Plan/feature-x.md:15-42`), Research File, State (`Backlog` / `In Progress` / `Done` / `Blocked`).
- `_Test/` — testing documents.
- `_Documentation/` — architecture guides, user guides, how-to, best practices.
- `_Prototype/` — throwaway prototypes, one per subfolder, each independently runnable (own deps + `README.md`). No imports between `_Prototype/` and `src/`.
- `_Agent Logs/` — auto-generated by an agent-logger hook (e.g., from claude-code-essentials). Do not delete or modify log files during a session.
- Each direct subdirectory of the repo root should have its own `CLAUDE.md` (purpose, patterns, deps, pitfalls).
- After fixing a bug or recovering from a mistake, document the root cause in the relevant folder's `CLAUDE.md`.

## Repo `CLAUDE.md` vs `MEMORY.md` — no duplication, keep `MEMORY.md` thin

<!-- [UNIVERSAL] — applies to anyone using both files. -->

- `CLAUDE.md` = **stable** project context: structure, architecture, how-to guides.
- `MEMORY.md` = **thin index**. It auto-loads at session start, so size is a permanent token tax — keep it short.
  - Inline-OK: one-line changelog entries, quick-reference shortcuts/commands.
  - **Link only** (don't paste): lessons, gotchas, deep learnings, post-incident write-ups. Store the detail in `_Documentation/` (or a dedicated `_Documentation/Learnings/` subfolder) and reference it from `MEMORY.md` as `- [Title](path/to/file.md) — one-line hook`.
- If a fact fits both `CLAUDE.md` and `MEMORY.md`, put it in `CLAUDE.md` only — `MEMORY.md` links rather than copies.

## Implementation process

<!-- [OPINION] — TDD-first vertical-slice approach. Swap if you ship differently. -->

1. **Research** first.
2. **Plan** from research. Plans must be **vertical slices** (data → processing → presentation → test), each demoable on its own. If a slice can't be tested end-to-end, it's a layer — split it.
3. **TDD** — write failing tests first, then the implementation that makes them pass, then refactor. The plan's "Tests" section must enumerate cases before implementation. If a task doesn't suit TDD (one-off scripts, UI styling, exploration), flag it and ask before proceeding.
4. **Implement.**
5. **Testing summary** — document coverage.

For large-scale work (multiple slices, external systems, expensive-to-reverse architectural decisions, multi-session), **recommend** `/grill-me` once after the initial plan exists; don't auto-invoke. Skip for one-off fixes, refactors, tactical work.

## Agent operation

<!-- [UNIVERSAL] — these rules apply to anyone using Claude Code subagents. -->

**Subagents and skills first.** Always consider them before solving a task directly.

**Background agents** (`run_in_background: true`) cannot prompt for permissions and stall silently if a tool requires approval. Rules:
- Always set `mode: "acceptEdits"` — lets them write files, blocks bash and other privileged ops.
- If an agent needs bash or privileged perms, run it in the **foreground** (no `run_in_background`).
- Never use `bypassPermissions` for background agents.
- Web research agents can take 5–7+ minutes — use timeouts up to 600000ms when polling. The output file only populates on completion; empty ≠ failed. Prefer `TaskOutput` with `block: true` over short polling loops.

**Scoping rules — always enforce in the agent prompt:**
1. State the EXACT output file path (e.g., "Save to `_Research/topic-name.md`").
2. State what NOT to do (e.g., "Do not edit existing files, do not run bash").
3. Research agents: "Research only. Write a single markdown file to `_Research/`. Do not modify any other files."
4. Plan agents: "Create a plan file at `_Plan/plan-name.md`. Do not implement anything."

## Bash commands must be atomic — no compound shell expressions

<!-- [UNIVERSAL] — applies to anyone shipping hooks/plugins/skills that issue Bash calls. -->

Every Bash call (direct or generated inside plugins/skills/agents/hooks) must be a single atomic operation. **No** `&&`, `||`, `;`, `|`, `|&`, `&` (background), subshells `(...)`, `$(...)`, backticks, heredocs. Drop non-essential redirects like `2>/dev/null` — the Bash tool handles stderr and exit codes natively.

Exception: operators fully inside a quoted string the shell doesn't interpret (e.g., `python foo.py --sql "SELECT a || b FROM t"`).

Rewrite patterns:
- "A then B" → two sequential Bash calls.
- "A, if fails B" → issue A, read exit code, conditionally issue B.
- "pipe A to B" → run A, read output, pass to B as args — or wrap in a Python script and call it atomically.
- "multiple related commands" → write a script file, invoke it as one call.

Why it matters: Claude Code matches permission rules per-subcommand. Compound expressions fall through to interactive prompts, which background subagents can't answer — the call stalls silently.

## Never embed local absolute paths in tracked files

<!-- [UNIVERSAL] — a privacy + portability rule. Keep this. -->

Files under any repo root (`.md`, `.json`, `.yml`, `.py`, etc.) must never contain user-revealing local paths: `C:\Users\<name>\...`, `/home/<name>/...`, `/Users/<name>/...`, `~/.claude/projects/...`, `~/.claude/plugins/cache/<id>/...`. Includes prose, code examples, error-message quotes, "source:" footers.

Use instead: `~/` for portable user-home refs, `${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}` / `${CLAUDE_SKILL_DIR}` inside plugin or skill markdown, or `<placeholder>` forms (`<repo-root>`, `<plugin-root>`, `<id>`) in prose.

Before any Write/Edit under a repo: if content contains `:\`, `~/`, or `/home/`, rewrite as a placeholder. Git history leaks are permanent.
```

